summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1461: Pachirisu (Call of Legends)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1461: Pachirisu (Call of Legends)
body:
Pachirisu was built to get Energy quickly and then lose it all in a single attack. The damage wasn’t really worth it in this case, but what if you could move that Energy to something that could use it? Well, Shaymin did exist… But you needed a Pokemon that could use that Energy, too. Luckily, once the Black & White set was released, an obvious choice came along. Suddenly, Pachirisu had a chance despite not using the combo it was built for at all.

60 HP was pretty sad. It was low enough, in fact, that the late portions of the HGSS-On format were a nightmare. Darkrai EX could take it out on the Bench in 2 hits while smashing the Active Pokemon at the same time, which caused a lot of issues. The x2 Fighting Weakness was one of those things that technically existed but didn’t matter since Fighting-types that mattered could crush Pachirisu’s low HP anyway. The -20 Metal Resistance? Not that important either. Being able to retreat for a single Energy was pretty cool if it somehow survived up front for a turn, at least.

Self-Generation was what made Pachirisu usable in the first place. When you put Pachirisu from your hand onto your Bench, you could attach up to 2 Lightning Energy cards from your hand onto Pachirisu. Pachirisu couldn’t use that Energy very well, so Shaymin from the Unleashed set would then be put into play to move that Energy onto a big attacker. The big attacker that was notable was Zekrom, which could get a Bolt Strike up in a single turn if the set-up went well. The deck got some solid results, but did struggle against Fighting-types and, soon, Gothitelle which shut off Poke-Powers.Tornadus was soon released and worked as a solid back-up attacker, while people would commonly toss in something like Magby to Burn Gothitelle and get rid of its lock, and the deck known as ZPST was born.

Shocking Bolt tried to use that Energy Pachirisu got in a more direct way, but 50 damage for 2 Energy with those Energy going into the Lost Zone was not going to cut it. Just hand the Energy off to something better.

Pachirisu was a big player in a surprisingly good deck. While it had its match-up issues and had a lot of moving parts, a fast Zekrom was really hard to stop. The deck’s popularity fell off with all the Pokemon EX showing up later on, as well as the introduction of Eelektrik, which was a bit slower but much more reliable throughout a game. Still, being in a tournament-worthy deck was a big accomplishment in itself, and sometimes just getting a couple of Energy attachments to hand off to something better was a good enough role.

summary: Hi! I'm the anon who found a root fossil a while ago. Finally I got to Devon and now I have a male lileep. I haven't introduce...
question: Hi! I'm the anon who found a root fossil a while ago. Finally I got to Devon and now I have a male lileep. I haven't introduce him to the rest of my team yet, thought you might have some advice on how to do it.  My team is a female pelipper who's been with me since she was a young wingull, and a male wooper who I catched this year.
answer:
When it comes to Wooper, they are naturally quite friendly and trusting (since they have no natural predators) and so I doubt you will have any issues introducing your new Lileep to him. 

Pelipper tend not to be very territorial, but also can take a while to build trust. She will most likely watch from a distance and mimic how you handle the newest addition to your family, so being a good role model is key!

-Thea

blog.name: friendsafariserver
blog.title: Friend Safari!
blog.description:
Friend Safari is a SFW, OC-friendly, paragraph-style roleplay server for main series Pokémon games. From Kanto to Alola, the whole Pokémon world is your Cloyster! Members of this server are allowed a total of four played characters, with at least one required to be canonical.

The server is run by a team of five mods who you can learn more about via the mods page. We cultivate an easygoing and open atmosphere, with member comfort and happiness being our top priority.

All of the links are in the drop down menu under Rowlet, labeled Pokémon! Hovering over each Pokémon will tell you what page they link to!
